Dear solvers of the New York Times:

I assure you no constructors go out of their way to include ATSEA or ASEA. It just so happens that they are very convenient crossword filler (common vowels and consonants) and sometimes they are just unavoidable for the great good of the grid. Obviously they are archaic, or at least overly formal, but that doesn’t mean they can’t be used in crosswords. But thanks for the advice. I dislike it as much as you.
